WEEK 5 REPORT – MASTER DATASET & SUPPLIER EVALUATION
Objective

To consolidate processed supply data into a unified master dataset and develop structured metrics for evaluating supplier reliability, cost efficiency, and logistics performance.

Activities Performed
Day 16 – Master Dataset Creation
Integrated cleaned procurement data into a centralized dataset for analysis
Engineered key features including total cost, defect impact, and normalized cost and defect scores
Applied standardization techniques to evaluate supplier performance consistency
Developed an initial composite scoring model based on cost and defect metrics

Day 17 – Supplier Reliability & Risk Scoring
Designed reliability scoring using defect rate, cost efficiency, and stability indicators
Computed risk scores based on supplier variability and defect contribution
Categorized suppliers into reliability and risk segments for evaluation
Enhanced dataset with structured performance indicators for decision analysis

Day 18 – Logistics Efficiency & Final Insights
Evaluated supplier efficiency using cost, defect rate, and overall procurement impact
Ranked suppliers based on performance metrics to identify top and low performers
Identified high-risk and cost-inefficient suppliers for operational review
Generated key performance indicators and summary insights for business understanding

Results
A comprehensive master dataset was successfully created for supplier-level analysis
Supplier reliability and risk scoring models were implemented for structured evaluation
Key inefficiencies and high-risk suppliers were identified using performance metrics
The dataset was prepared for advanced analytics, decision modeling, and dashboard integration

Conclusion

Week 5 established the foundation for supplier performance analytics by transforming raw procurement data into a structured evaluation system. The developed scoring models enabled systematic identification of reliable and high-risk vendors, supporting data-driven decision-making in logistics operations.